// Researched content for mexico-cancun-riviera-maya-b. Written per property.
module.exports = {
  'grand-palladium-kantenah-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Part of the sprawling Grand Palladium Riviera Maya complex (Kantenah shares grounds and restaurants with the neighboring Colonial and White Sand hotels), guests here move freely between a long run of pools, a full dive center, tennis courts, and a spa. Kids and teens have dedicated clubs and a waterpark-style pool, while the beach — a stretch of the Akumal coastline that periodically deals with sargassum — is serviceable rather than a highlight. Snorkeling trips to Akumal Bay's turtles and day trips to Tulum's ruins and the Coba pyramid are easy add-ons.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Kantenah sits on the Akumal coast about 45 minutes south of Cancun International Airport, in the resort corridor between Playa del Carmen and Tulum. It's a genuinely large, multi-hotel all-inclusive built for families, with three interconnecting properties sharing a long beach and dozens of restaurants. Cleanliness and service both score strongly, and value holds up well for the price bracket; food and atmosphere are more middling marks, and the beach itself only rates a soft 6.3 given the seaweed that periodically reaches this part of the coast. Plan around the roughly April–October sargassum season if beach time is the priority, and expect a resort built around volume rather than intimacy.`,
  },
  'the-royal-cancun-all-suites-resort': {
    activities: `The Royal Cancun is an all-suites property on Cancun's northern Hotel Zone shore, where the water is calmer than the surf-exposed southern beaches, making it a genuine swimming beach rather than a lounging-only one. Every suite has a kitchenette and a private whirlpool tub, and the resort runs a supervised kids' club, a playground, watersports rentals, and a fishing charter desk. Its position near the Hotel Zone's northern tip puts the ferry to Isla Mujeres and the underwater sculpture museum (MUSA) within easy reach, along with Coco Bongo and the Zona Hotelera's restaurant strip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, The Royal Cancun sits on a sheltered stretch of the Hotel Zone that families gravitate toward for swimmable water rather than the wave-heavy southern beaches. Every score here lands high — cleanliness, service, and room quality are all standout — and the resort's suite-style layout (kitchen, living area, separate bedroom) makes it a natural fit for multi-generational trips or longer stays. It's a family property with a full kids' program, not a couples retreat. Hurricane season runs roughly June through November, so late fall through spring is the more settled window for a Cancun beach vacation.`,
  },
  'garza-blanca-resort-and-spa-cancun': {
    activities: `Garza Blanca's Punta Sam location — on the quieter Costa Mujeres side north of the Hotel Zone — gives it a wide, less-trafficked beach and calmer water than central Cancun. A rooftop infinity pool and seven pools scattered through the property are a genuine draw, alongside its spa, a kids' club, and yoga classes. The Punta Sam ferry to Isla Mujeres is a short walk away, making a Playa Norte day trip or Garrafón reef excursion simple, while Cancun's Hotel Zone nightlife is a 30-plus-minute drive rather than a walk.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This property sits on Costa Mujeres near Punta Sam, roughly 35–40 minutes from Cancun International Airport — further out than Hotel Zone resorts, but in exchange guests get a quieter beach and newer construction. Nearly every rating here is exceptional: rooms, service, cleanliness, and food all score in the low-to-mid 9s, making it one of the stronger all-around performers on this stretch of coast. It suits families and couples alike, with elegant suites and a full kids' club. Because it's set apart from Cancun's main strip, renting a car or budgeting for taxis is worth factoring in; November through April brings the driest, least humid weather.`,
  },
  'the-royal-haciendas-all-suites-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `The Royal Haciendas sits just north of central Playa del Carmen, an all-suites property with a waterpark-style kids' pool, a swim-up bar, tennis, a nightclub, and an on-site dive shop offering trips to the reefs off Playa and the ferry-accessible walls of Cozumel. Its beach fronts the Mesoamerican Reef system, making snorkeling straight off the sand a realistic option on calm days. Fifth Avenue's shops and restaurants are a short taxi ride away, as are day trips to the cenotes and ruins scattered through the Riviera Maya.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Located a few minutes' drive from downtown Playa del Carmen and about 45 minutes from Cancun International Airport, The Royal Haciendas is an all-suites, family-oriented resort with kitchenettes and separate living areas in every unit. Cleanliness, room quality, and value all score strongly, while pool and atmosphere are more middling — the pool complex is smaller relative to some of the mega-resorts further south. It works well for families wanting proximity to Playa's restaurant scene without staying in the town center itself. Quintana Roo's dry season (roughly November to April) is the most reliable stretch for beach days, with more frequent afternoon showers from June onward.`,
  },
  'turquoize-at-hyatt-ziva-cancun': {
    activities: `Turquoize is the adults-only enclave within Hyatt Ziva Cancun, occupying a stretch of the Hotel Zone's calmer northern beach with a private rooftop pool, butler service, and access to the broader resort's restaurants and watersports. The beach here is one of the better swimming beaches in the zone, sheltered enough for real ocean time rather than just photos. Its Hotel Zone position puts the Isla Mujeres ferry, the MUSA underwater museum's snorkel and dive excursions, and Cancun's restaurant and nightlife strip all within a short drive.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Fly into Cancun International Airport for Turquoize, which sits within the Hotel Zone on the calmer side of the peninsula. Rooms, cleanliness, and location all score exceptionally, and the beach is a genuine strength — a rarity in a zone where erosion has hit many properties. The catch, per guest feedback, is that this adults-only section shares grounds with the larger all-ages Hyatt Ziva resort, so it isn't fully walled off from families. It suits couples wanting five-star service and a Hotel Zone address without leaving the Hyatt ecosystem. Visit outside hurricane season, roughly June–November, for the most settled weather.`,
  },
  'family-selection-at-grand-palladium-select-costa-mujeres': {
    activities: `This is the family wing of the Grand Palladium Select Costa Mujeres complex, with a dedicated kids' club for the very youngest guests, a waterpark-style kids' pool, and babysitting on request, all set on the calmer Costa Mujeres coastline north of Cancun. The wider Palladium property brings extra pools, a spa, and a full restaurant lineup. The area's biggest draws are its own quiet beach and the Isla Mujeres ferry from nearby Punta Sam, plus Cancun's Hotel Zone and downtown market a 40-minute drive south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Fly into Cancun International Airport for this Costa Mujeres property, about 45 minutes north of the airport on a newer, less developed stretch of coast than the Hotel Zone. Rooms and cleanliness both rate strongly, and the resort's family-first design — with a kids' club for under-4s and a waterpark pool — sets it apart from adults-oriented neighbors in Playa Mujeres. Its remove from central Cancun means fewer walkable options outside the resort, so plan on organized excursions or a rental car for Isla Mujeres or downtown trips. The driest, most comfortable months run November through April.`,
  },
  'the-reef-28': {
    activities: `The Reef 28 is a boutique, design-forward adults-only property in Playa del Carmen with a heated pool, a small gym, yoga classes, and an on-site dive operation that runs trips to the reefs offshore and the ferry-accessible walls of Cozumel. Its rooftop nightclub and central location make it a natural base for exploring Fifth Avenue's restaurants and bars on foot rather than relying on resort grounds for entertainment. The beach is the resort's acknowledged weak point — narrow and less swimmable than the Riviera Maya's better stretches — so most guests treat the pool and town as the main draw.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `The Reef 28 sits inside Playa del Carmen proper, a roughly 45-minute drive from Cancun International Airport, putting Fifth Avenue's shopping and dining within walking distance. Rooms and cleanliness both score strongly, and the design-hotel feel suits couples over families. The honest caveat is the beach — a soft 4.5, among the lower marks in our database, reflecting Playa's narrower, more built-up shoreline in this stretch compared to resorts further down the coast. Book it for the town location and boutique atmosphere rather than for beach time, and consider a Cozumel ferry day trip to make up for it. November through April brings the calmest seas and least rain.`,
  },
  'el-dorado-casitas-royale': {
    activities: `El Dorado Casitas Royale is a Karisma "Gourmet Inclusive" property built around romance — private plunge pools and swim-up terraces in many casitas, a lazy river, horseback riding, tennis, and a spa, plus a shared dive shop for reef trips. It's calmer than its livelier sister resort next door, aimed squarely at honeymooners and anniversary trips rather than nightlife. The wider Riviera Maya's cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Xcaret park are all within an hour's drive for day-trip variety beyond the resort grounds.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 40 minutes north, El Dorado Casitas Royale is an adults-only resort built for couples, with private plunge pools a signature feature of its casita rooms. Cleanliness, service, and room quality all score in the low-to-mid 9s — genuinely excellent — while the beach is the honest weak point at 4, one of the lower marks in our database, a reflection of the Riviera Maya's uneven natural shoreline in this stretch rather than resort upkeep. Treat the pools and grounds as the primary water feature and the beach as a bonus. November through April is the most reliable season for calm seas and lower humidity.`,
  },
  'el-dorado-seaside-suites': {
    activities: `El Dorado Seaside Suites is part of the same Karisma cluster as Casitas Royale, an adults-only, all-suites property with swim-up-bar pools, tennis, and a nightclub for evenings, plus a shared spa and dive shop. Rooms lean toward suites rather than standalone casitas, making it a slightly more resort-scaled version of its sister properties. Guests use it as a base for Riviera Maya day trips — Xcaret, the Tulum ruins, or a Cozumel ferry crossing for reef diving — rather than relying solely on the beach out front.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Karisma property is reached via Cancun International Airport and sits in the same cluster as El Dorado Casitas Royale along the Riviera Maya coast, roughly 45 minutes south of the airport. Cleanliness and service both score well, and it's an adults-only resort suited to couples wanting an all-suites layout with swim-up access. The beach, like its sister properties along this stretch, is the softest score at 4 — among the lower marks in our database — so expect the pools to carry the water-based recreation. Food rates solidly without being a standout. Plan trips for November through April for the calmest, least humid conditions.`,
  },
  'the-fives-oceanfront-puerto-morelos': {
    activities: `This boutique, roughly 90-room property sits directly on Puerto Morelos's stretch of the Mesoamerican Reef, a protected marine park close enough to shore for snorkeling and diving straight from the beach. On site, guests have a gym, bicycles, windsurfing and other watersports rentals, yoga classes, and a spa, with the fishing-village town of Puerto Morelos — smaller and less built-up than Cancun or Playa del Carmen — a short walk away for its market and seafood restaurants. Fishing charters out of the town's marina are another easy add-on.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `The Fives Oceanfront sits in Puerto Morelos, about 20 minutes south of Cancun International Airport, making it one of the more convenient bases on this coast without the density of the Hotel Zone. Rooms and cleanliness both score well, and its boutique scale suits families or couples wanting a quieter, more design-forward stay than the larger all-inclusives. The beach rates only a middling 5.3, reflecting the mixed sand-and-rock shoreline typical of Puerto Morelos's protected reef frontage. Book it for the reef access and low-key village setting rather than for a classic wide sand beach, and visit outside hurricane season for the calmest water.`,
  },
  'fiesta-americana-condesa-cancun': {
    activities: `Fiesta Americana Condesa Cancun sits mid-Hotel Zone with one of the area's better swimming beaches, backed by a large pool complex with a slide and water features, a kids' club, tennis, fishing charters, and a dive operation for reef trips. Evenings run to organized entertainment and a swim-up bar; the Zona Hotelera's restaurants, Coco Bongo, and the MUSA underwater museum's snorkel excursions are all a short drive away. Downtown Cancun's markets and cheaper local eateries are reachable by taxi for a change of pace from the resort strip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Fiesta Americana property is a straightforward Hotel Zone stay via Cancun International Airport, built for families with a full kids' program and a beach that scores a genuine 8 — one of the better marks on this stretch of coast. Cleanliness and service both rate strongly, while food and atmosphere land more in the middle of the pack. It's a reliable, resort-scale choice rather than a boutique one, well suited to families wanting beach access without a long transfer. Hurricane season runs roughly June through November, so late fall through spring brings the most settled weather for beach time.`,
  },
  'mahekal-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Mahekal's signature feature is its thatched-roof palapa bungalows scattered through gardens and along the beach — a deliberately low-key, jungle-lodge alternative to Playa del Carmen's high-rise resorts. Guests spend time in the pool, on bicycles rented for exploring town, at yoga classes, or simply in a hammock on their palapa's private terrace; the swim-up bar and evening entertainment cover the resort side of things. Its location two blocks from Fifth Avenue's quieter northern end puts Playa's restaurants and the Cozumel ferry within easy walking distance.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Mahekal sits directly on the beach at the quiet north end of Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun International Airport. Rooms deliberately skip televisions in favor of the palapa-and-hammock atmosphere, which reviewers either love or find limiting — worth knowing before booking. Location and atmosphere are its strongest marks, and food rates well above average for an all-inclusive; palapa roofs do let in more ambient noise than a standard hotel room, something light sleepers should weigh. It suits families and couples wanting a beachfront, low-rise alternative to Playa's bigger towers. November through April brings the calmest seas and least rain.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-playacar': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Playacar sits in the gated Playacar residential district south of central Playa del Carmen, with a genuinely wide beach, a dive center, a kids' club, and the swim-up bars and nightly entertainment typical of the Riu chain. Playacar's own golf course and small aviary are nearby, and the resort runs snorkeling trips out to the reef. Fifth Avenue's shops and restaurants and the Cozumel ferry terminal are a short taxi ride north for a day away from the resort grounds.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 45 minutes south, Riu Playacar sits in the quieter, more residential Playacar area rather than downtown Playa del Carmen. Beach and location both score well — Playacar's beach is one of the area's better swimming stretches — while food and atmosphere are the resort's softer marks, typical of the Riu chain's higher-volume buffet model. It's a solid family pick for guests who want a real beach and easy access to Playa's town center without staying in the middle of it. Visit November through April for the driest, calmest conditions.`,
  },
  'the-royal-sands-all-suites-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `The Royal Sands sits at the northern curve of Cancun's Hotel Zone, where the beach is genuinely swimmable rather than surf-battered — its strong beach score reflects that. All-suites accommodations come with kitchenettes and private balconies, and the resort runs a kids' club, tennis, a dive shop, and fishing charters alongside the standard pool and swim-up bar setup. The Isla Mujeres ferry and the MUSA underwater sculpture museum's snorkel trips are both close by, as is the Hotel Zone's restaurant and nightlife corridor.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Fly into Cancun International Airport for The Royal Sands, positioned on one of the Hotel Zone's calmer, more protected beaches. Beach, location, and cleanliness all score strongly, making it one of the more consistent family all-suites options in the zone; food and atmosphere are more middling by comparison. The suite layout — separate living and sleeping areas plus a kitchenette — suits families or groups wanting more space than a standard hotel room. Hurricane season runs roughly June through November, so late fall through spring is the safer window for beach-focused travel.`,
  },
  'royal-hideaway-playacar': {
    activities: `Royal Hideaway Playacar is a Barceló-run, adults-only resort in the gated Playacar district, built around six restaurants that all require reservations rather than a buffet, six pools, and a full spa. It's a quieter, more formal property than Playa's livelier resorts — entertainment is deliberately restrained — and its beachfront position gives direct access to Playacar's stretch of sand. Fifth Avenue's shops and restaurants, the Cozumel ferry, and Playacar's own golf course are all a short taxi ride from the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Royal Hideaway sits in Playacar, the gated residential zone south of downtown Playa del Carmen. Food, location, and sleep quality all rate well, and the reservations-only restaurant model (no buffet) is a deliberate point of distinction reviewers note, for better or worse depending on preference for spontaneity. Rooms are well kept but some guests describe them as dated relative to newer competitors. It's built for couples seeking a formal, low-key adults-only stay rather than nightlife. November through April brings the most reliable weather for beach days.`,
  },
  'nickelodeon-hotels-and-resorts-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `This Karisma-run, Nickelodeon-themed resort is built around family entertainment: a waterpark with slides for both little and big kids, character meet-and-greets, a lazy river, and swim-up suites are the daily draw rather than the beach. Its Playa Paraiso setting places it along the same stretch of coast as the Iberostar Paraiso complex, with the Riviera Maya's cenotes, Xcaret, and the Tulum ruins all reachable as day trips. The pool complex, not the shoreline, is genuinely the property's headline feature.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Located in Playa Paraiso on the Riviera Maya coast, about an hour south of Cancun International Airport, this resort is built for theming and water features rather than a beach vacation. The pool score is a real strength, but the beach rates a soft 3.8 — one of the lower marks in our database — because rock groins placed to control erosion have left little usable sand in front of the hotel. Book it for the water park, kids' club, and Nickelodeon branding rather than for oceanfront lounging. It suits families with young children specifically; November through April is the Riviera Maya's driest stretch.`,
  },
  'barcelo-maya-colonial': {
    activities: `Barceló Maya Colonial is one wing of the large multi-hotel Barceló Maya complex, which shares its beach, a FlowRider surf simulator, mini golf, tennis, and a waterpark-style pool area across all the connected properties. Kids' and teens' clubs run daily programs, and the resort's dive shop organizes reef trips along this stretch of the Riviera Maya, with Xpu-Ha beach and the Puerto Aventuras marina town nearby for a change of scenery. Evening entertainment and a nightclub round out the resort side of things.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Barceló Maya Colonial sits near Puerto Aventuras, about 50 minutes south of Cancun International Airport, as part of a sprawling multi-property complex built for families and groups. Sleep quality and value both score reasonably well, while food, pool, and atmosphere are its more middling marks — typical trade-offs for a resort built at this scale. The FlowRider and shared water features are a genuine differentiator for families with older kids or teens. Book with realistic expectations about buffet-style dining at this size, and plan around the roughly June–November hurricane season for calmer beach weather.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-kukulkan': {
    activities: `Riu Palace Kukulkan is an adults-only property mid-Hotel Zone with a genuinely strong beach — one of the better-rated stretches in the area — backed by pools, a swim-up bar, and the Riu chain's signature all-night buffet and entertainment schedule. Its central Zona Hotelera position puts Coco Bongo, the Forum shopping center, and the MUSA underwater museum's dive and snorkel excursions all within a short walk or taxi ride. Yoga classes round out the daytime resort activities.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Riu Palace Kukulkan sits centrally in the Hotel Zone, an easy base for exploring the wider strip on foot. Rooms and cleanliness both score exceptionally, and the beach is a genuine strength in a zone where erosion has hurt many neighboring properties. It's an adults-only resort suited to couples wanting a livelier, more central Hotel Zone location than the quieter northern end. Book November through April for the calmest seas; hurricane season, roughly June–November, brings the highest chance of disruption.`,
  },
  'sunscape-cancun-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Sunscape Cancun runs a full family program — kids' and teens' clubs, a heated pool, fishing charters, and a dive shop for reef trips — alongside the swim-up bars and nightclub typical of the brand. Its Hotel Zone position gives reasonable beach access, and the resort leans on organized entertainment and theme nights to fill evenings. Isla Mujeres's ferry and the MUSA underwater sculpture museum are both within easy reach for a day trip away from the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sunscape Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone, reached via Cancun International Airport, and is built as a mid-tier, family-friendly all-inclusive. Beach and location are decent, workaday marks, while food and atmosphere are its weaker scores — the buffet-driven dining and lower-key evening scene draw more mixed reviews than the resort's beach or rooms. It suits families on a budget rather than travelers chasing a gourmet or lively nightlife experience. Late fall through spring avoids both the region's rainiest months and peak hurricane season.`,
  },
  'generations-riviera-maya-resort': {
    activities: `Generations Riviera Maya is a Karisma "gourmet all-inclusive" built around suite-style rooms — many with separate living rooms — a lazy river, a kids' club, and swim-up bars, with the beach playing a secondary role to the pool and dining program. Its position along the Riviera Maya corridor puts Xcaret, Xel-Ha, the Tulum ruins, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue all within reach as excursions. The resort emphasizes upscale, à la carte dining over buffet volume.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Karisma property sits along the Riviera Maya coast, reached via Cancun International Airport, and is built for families wanting spacious suites and a gourmet dining format rather than a wide beach. Room quality and sleep quality both score exceptionally, and value holds up well; the beach, however, rates a soft 4 — among the lower marks in our database — a reflection of the small, rocky shoreline in front of the property rather than a resort-wide issue. Treat the pools as the primary swimming option and plan a beach day trip (Xpu-Ha or Playa del Carmen) if sand matters. November through April is the most reliable season.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-peninsula': {
    activities: `Riu Palace Peninsula sits at the Hotel Zone's northern tip, giving it calmer water than the surf-facing southern beaches along with a dedicated adult pool, a dive shop, and the Riu chain's standard all-inclusive buffet and entertainment format. Its position near Punta Cancun puts the Isla Mujeres ferry terminal, the Forum shopping center, and Coco Bongo within easy reach, alongside snorkel and dive trips to the MUSA underwater museum.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Riu Palace Peninsula occupies the calmer northern curve of the Hotel Zone, a genuine advantage for swimming compared to properties further south. Beach, location, and sleep quality all score solidly, making it a dependable family choice; food and atmosphere sit more in the middle of the pack, consistent with the brand's buffet-driven model. It works well for families wanting Hotel Zone convenience with easier ferry access to Isla Mujeres. Late fall through spring offers the calmest seas and lowest rain chances.`,
  },
  'secrets-playa-mujeres-golf-and-spa-resort': {
    activities: `Secrets Playa Mujeres is built around its Greg Norman-designed golf course, a genuine rarity among Riviera Maya all-inclusives, alongside a full spa, multiple pools, tennis, and an adults-only atmosphere with nightly entertainment and a nightclub. Its Costa Mujeres setting north of Cancun gives it a quieter beach than the Hotel Zone, and the Isla Mujeres ferry from nearby Punta Sam makes for an easy day trip. Reef snorkeling and Cancun's downtown market are both within reach for guests wanting to leave the grounds.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly 40 minutes north, Secrets Playa Mujeres sits on the calmer Costa Mujeres coast rather than the Hotel Zone proper. Sleep quality and location both score strongly, and the golf course is a genuine differentiator for an adults-only resort in this region. Food and value are solid without being standouts. It suits couples wanting golf, spa time, and a quieter beach setting over Cancun's livelier strip. November through April brings the most comfortable weather for both golf and the beach.`,
  },
  'beach-palace': {
    activities: `Beach Palace sits mid-Hotel Zone with a genuinely strong beach, backed by a lazy river, pool slide, and water features that keep families occupied without leaving the property. A kids' club, spa, and swim-up bar round out the daytime program, with a nightclub and evening entertainment for later hours. The MUSA underwater museum's snorkel and dive trips and Isla Mujeres's ferry are both a short drive away for a change of pace.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Beach Palace occupies a central Hotel Zone stretch with one of the area's better beaches, rating a genuine 8. Cleanliness and service both score exceptionally, and the resort's family-focused water features (lazy river, slide) are a real strength for younger kids; pool and atmosphere are its more middling marks by comparison. It's a reliable, family-oriented choice for a classic Hotel Zone beach stay. Hurricane season runs roughly June through November, so late fall through spring is the calmer window.`,
  },
  'sandos-cancun': {
    activities: `Sandos Cancun is an adults-only resort built around its "Total Gourmet" dining concept, with several à la carte restaurants alongside the buffet, a tiered pool, and a beachfront setting in the Hotel Zone. Evenings lean into the resort's own entertainment program rather than off-site nightlife, though Coco Bongo and the Forum shopping center are a short drive away. The quieter, adults-only atmosphere is the property's main draw over any single standout activity.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Sandos Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone as one of the area's longer-established adults-only resorts, which shows in some dated fixtures and rooms despite decent overall upkeep. Beach and food both score reasonably well, while pool and atmosphere are more middling. It suits couples and solo travelers wanting a quieter, no-kids environment and attentive staff over cutting-edge design. Late fall through spring brings the most settled weather, avoiding both peak hurricane season and the wettest months.`,
  },
  'iberostar-waves-paraiso-beach': {
    activities: `Iberostar Waves Paraíso Beach — recently rebranded from Iberostar Paraíso Beach under Iberostar's family-focused "Waves" line — sits within the large Playa Paraiso complex, sharing an 18-hole golf course, dive center, and beachfront with its sister hotels. Archery, tennis, bicycles, and a kids' club fill the daytime schedule, with a nightclub and evening entertainment for later hours. The Riviera Maya's cenotes and the Tulum ruins are both within an hour's drive for excursions beyond the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, this Iberostar property sits in Playa Paraiso, part of a large shared complex roughly 40 minutes south of the airport. It suits families looking for the resort-scale amenities (golf, dive center, kids' club) that come with staying inside a multi-hotel complex. Food, beach, and atmosphere are its more moderate scores, typical of a resort built for volume rather than boutique polish; cleanliness and service hold up better. Book November through April for the Riviera Maya's driest, calmest stretch.`,
  },
  'iberostar-waves-paraiso-del-mar': {
    activities: `Like its sister hotel Paraíso Beach, Iberostar Waves Paraíso del Mar shares the Playa Paraiso complex's golf course, dive center, and beachfront, with its own teens' club, mini golf, archery, and nightclub layered on top. The shared amenities across the complex mean guests here have access to more restaurants and pools than a standalone property of similar size. Riviera Maya staples — Xcaret, the Tulum ruins, and cenote day trips — are all within an hour.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Iberostar property, part of the Playa Paraiso complex south of Cancun, is reached via Cancun International Airport in about 40 minutes. Its ratings closely mirror its sister hotel Paraíso Beach — solid cleanliness and service, more middling food and atmosphere — reflecting a shared operation built for family groups rather than boutique intimacy. The teens' club and golf course are genuine differentiators for families with older kids. November through April remains the most reliable season for beach weather on this coast.`,
  },
  'grand-palladium-white-sand-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Grand Palladium White Sand is part of the same Riviera Maya Palladium complex as Kantenah and Colonial, giving guests access to a shared run of pools, an under-4s kids' club, tennis, mini golf, and a dive center along this stretch of coast in the Solidaridad municipality between Playa del Carmen and Akumal. Nightly entertainment and a nightclub cover the evenings, while day trips to Xcaret, the Tulum ruins, or Cozumel's dive sites are all within reach.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly 40–45 minutes north, White Sand sits within the large multi-hotel Grand Palladium complex on the Riviera Maya coast. Cleanliness, service, and sleep quality all score solidly, while beach and food are more middling — typical for a resort built at this scale with shared facilities across several connected hotels. It's a family-oriented pick that benefits from the sheer volume of restaurants and pools available complex-wide. Plan around the wetter summer months; November through April brings the calmest seas.`,
  },
  'ocean-coral-and-turquesa': {
    activities: `Ocean Coral & Turquesa sits on the Puerto Morelos coast within the protected Mesoamerican Reef marine park, with a dive shop, archery, tennis, and a teens' club rounding out the on-site program alongside the standard pools and swim-up bar. The beach here sits inside a reef-protected zone, which keeps the water calm but also means less classic open sand than resorts further south. Puerto Morelos's low-key fishing-village center and its market are a short drive for a change of pace.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 20–25 minutes, Ocean Coral & Turquesa is one of the more convenient bases on this coast without the density of the Hotel Zone. Cleanliness and sleep quality both score well, while the beach rates a soft 4.8 — the marine park's reef protection limits how much sand and open water there is directly in front of the resort. It's a family property best booked for reef access and proximity to the airport rather than for classic wide-beach lounging. November through April remains the most settled season.`,
  },
  'ocean-riviera-paradise': {
    activities: `Ocean Riviera Paradise is a large, multi-themed resort north of central Playa del Carmen, split into sections with different design concepts, each with its own pools, an adult pool, and a teens' club alongside the family kids' club. The beach fronts a stretch of reef-protected coastline, which limits classic sand time but supports snorkeling on calm days. Playa's Fifth Avenue and the Cozumel ferry terminal are both a short taxi ride away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 40 minutes, Ocean Riviera Paradise is a large-scale family resort with a lower price point than many Riviera Maya competitors of similar size. Value and sleep quality both score well, while the beach rates a soft 4.8 — a reflection of the coastline's reef-protected, less sandy character in this stretch rather than a resort-specific issue. It suits families and groups wanting resort scale and proximity to Playa del Carmen's town center on a moderate budget. November through April is the most reliable window for calm seas.`,
  },
  'izla-hotel': {
    activities: `Izla Hotel, run by Fiesta Americana, sits on the quieter southern end of Isla Mujeres, a short ferry ride from Cancun, with two pools (including an adults-only pool), a spa, and a gym as the main on-site draws. The island itself is the real activity here — golf carts for exploring, Playa Norte's calm, shallow water at the north end, and snorkeling at the Garrafón reef park or the nearby MUSA underwater sculpture museum, reachable by boat.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Izla Hotel is reached by ferry from Cancun (via Puerto Juárez or the Hotel Zone terminals) to Isla Mujeres, then a short taxi to the island's quieter southern end, away from the main ferry-dock tourist strip. Rooms and cleanliness both score exceptionally, and the "all-inclusive" package here is worth double-checking at check-in, as some premium items can carry extra costs. It suits couples and families seeking a slower pace than Cancun proper, without the party crowd found on parts of the island. November through April brings the calmest ferry crossings and driest weather.`,
  },
  'hotel-nyx-cancun': {
    activities: `Hotel NYX sits on one of the better beaches in the middle of Cancun's Hotel Zone, next to Beach Palace, with a compact but lively layout built around a kids' club, yoga classes, and a spa. The beach — lined with loungers, daybeds, and palapas — is the property's clear strength, while the pool is smaller and gets crowded, a fair trade for its central position. Coco Bongo, the Forum shopping center, and MUSA snorkel trips are all a short walk or taxi ride away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Hotel NYX occupies a genuinely strong beach position mid-Hotel Zone, reflected in its 8.3 beach score. The pool, by contrast, is the resort's weak point at 5.8 — limited seating and a compact footprint are common guest complaints. Rooms cap at three guests, making it better suited to couples or small families than larger groups. It's a good value pick for beach-focused travelers willing to trade pool space for a central Hotel Zone location. Late fall through spring avoids the region's rainiest and stormiest months.`,
  },
  'ventus-at-marina-el-cid-spa-and-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Ventus at Marina El Cid sits on the Puerto Morelos coast next to the El Cid marina, with a kids' and teens' club, a private adult pool area, bicycles, and a spa built around Mayan-inspired treatments. The marina itself opens up fishing charters and boat excursions, while the reef just offshore — part of the same protected marine park that runs along this coast — supports snorkeling on calm days. Puerto Morelos's low-key town center is a short drive for a change of pace from resort grounds.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 20–25 minutes, this resort sits on the Puerto Morelos coast, closer to the airport than most Playa del Carmen or Tulum-area properties. Rooms score especially well, with suites and butler service drawing consistent praise, and cleanliness and service are both strong. The beach is the honest weak spot at 4.8 — sargassum and coastal erosion have affected this stretch, and the resort has been working on repairs. Book it for the marina setting, family amenities, and airport proximity rather than for a pristine beach. November through April is the calmer season.`,
  },
  'bahia-principe-explore-akumal': {
    activities: `Bahia Principe Explore Akumal (recently renamed from Bahia Principe Luxury Akumal) sits in the heart of Akumal — Mayan for "place of the turtles" — with a kids' club, casino, golf course, tennis, and a dive center that makes the famous Akumal Bay turtle-snorkeling site an easy outing. The wider Bahia Principe complex nearby adds more restaurants and pools within reach. Tulum's cliffside ruins and its cenotes are roughly 30 minutes south for a day trip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This resort is reached via Tulum International Airport rather than Cancun, reflecting Akumal's position further down the Riviera Maya coast, close to Tulum's ruins and cenote network. Beach, location, and sleep quality all score reasonably well, and the on-site casino and golf course are genuine differentiators for the area. Reservations for à la carte restaurants are worth booking well in advance through the resort's app. It suits families wanting a base closer to Tulum than Cancun. November through April remains the most settled season for both beach days and cenote visits.`,
  },
  'iberostar-selection-cancun': {
    activities: `Iberostar Selection Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone with a genuinely strong beach, a lazy river, a golf course nearby, and a full kids' and teens' club program alongside tennis and a dive center for reef trips. The "Selection" tier sits above Iberostar's standard product, with more polished dining and service. Isla Mujeres's ferry, the MUSA underwater museum, and downtown Cancun's markets are all within easy reach for excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, this Iberostar Selection property benefits from a strong Hotel Zone beach location, rating 8.3 — a real advantage given how many nearby resorts have lost sand to erosion. Location and service both score well, positioning it as a dependable family choice with resort-scale amenities including a lazy river and golf access. Food and pool round out as solid, middle-of-the-road marks. Late fall through spring brings the calmest seas and lowest rain chances for a beach-focused stay.`,
  },
  'the-fives-beach-hotel-and-residences': {
    activities: `The Fives Beach Hotel & Residences sits on the Playa del Carmen coast north of downtown, with residence-style suites, a dive shop, watersports rentals, a kids' and teens' club, and a nightclub for evenings. Its beachfront position gives access to the Mesoamerican Reef for snorkeling, and Fifth Avenue's restaurants and the Cozumel ferry are both a short drive south. The property's design leans boutique relative to the area's larger all-inclusives.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 40–45 minutes, The Fives Beach Hotel sits just outside central Playa del Carmen, offering residence-style rooms with more space than a standard hotel suite. Cleanliness and sleep quality both score well, while the beach is a more moderate 5.5 — reflecting the mixed sand-and-rock coastline typical of this part of the Riviera Maya rather than a specific flaw. It suits families wanting extra room and a boutique feel with easy access to Playa's town center. November through April is the most reliable season for beach weather.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-tequila': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Tequila sits inland of the beachfront within the Riu cluster near Playa del Carmen, sharing beach access with neighboring Riu properties while running its own kids' club, dive shop, and windsurfing and snorkeling rentals. Evening entertainment and a nightclub follow the standard Riu format. Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue and the Cozumel ferry are a short taxi ride away for guests wanting to leave the resort cluster.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Riu Tequila is positioned slightly back from the beachfront compared to its sister hotels in the same Riu cluster near Playa del Carmen, which shows up in its more modest 5 beach score. Value is a genuine strength here, and the resort delivers the reliable, if unspectacular, Riu buffet-and-entertainment format at a lower price point than many Riviera Maya competitors. It suits budget-conscious families willing to trade prime beachfront for savings. November through April brings the calmest, driest conditions.`,
  },
  'catalonia-grand-costa-mujeres-all-suites-and-spa': {
    activities: `Catalonia Grand Costa Mujeres is an all-suites property on the calmer Costa Mujeres coast north of Cancun, with a genuinely good swimming beach, a kids' and teens' club, a spa, and a nightclub for evenings. The area's newer, less developed setting compared to the Hotel Zone is part of the draw, with the Isla Mujeres ferry from nearby Punta Sam offering an easy day trip. Reservations for the property's à la carte restaurants are worth booking early, as they fill quickly.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly 40–45 minutes north, Catalonia Grand Costa Mujeres sits on Playa Mujeres's quieter shoreline. Beach and room quality both score well, and the all-suites format suits families wanting more space. Guest feedback flags the buffet as inconsistent and the spa as a mixed bag despite its polished setting — worth tempering expectations there even as the overall resort experience rates well. It's a solid family pick for beach quality outside the Hotel Zone's density. November through April remains the most settled season.`,
  },
  'grand-park-royal-cancun': {
    activities: `Grand Park Royal Cancun sits beachfront in the Hotel Zone with a lazy river, a kids' club, an adult pool, and a spa rounding out the on-site program alongside swim-up bars and evening entertainment. Its beach — one of the better-rated stretches on this list — makes it a solid base for straightforward Hotel Zone beach time. Isla Mujeres's ferry, Coco Bongo, and the MUSA underwater museum's dive and snorkel trips are all a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Grand Park Royal Cancun occupies a beachfront stretch of the Hotel Zone with a strong 8.3 beach score, a genuine differentiator in an area where several resorts have lost sand to erosion. Cleanliness and location both score well, while food and check-in processes draw more mixed guest feedback. It's an upper-middle-range, family-oriented choice built for straightforward beach access rather than boutique polish, and its position mid-zone keeps both the airport transfer and the Isla Mujeres ferry terminal reasonably short. Late fall through spring offers the calmest seas and lowest storm risk, while summer brings a higher chance of afternoon rain and tropical systems.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-caribe': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Caribe sits at the northern end of Cancun's Hotel Zone, closer to Punta Cancun and the Isla Mujeres ferry terminal than most, with a dive shop, tennis, a kids' club, and the standard Riu swim-up bar and nightly entertainment format. The beach here benefits from the calmer water typical of the zone's northern curve. Coco Bongo, the Forum shopping center, and downtown Cancun's markets are all within easy reach.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Riu Caribe sits at the Hotel Zone's calmer northern tip, giving it decent beach and location scores. Value and room quality both rate well, making it a dependable, moderately priced choice within the Riu portfolio; food and atmosphere are its more middling marks, consistent with the brand's buffet-driven approach. It suits families wanting Hotel Zone convenience and easy ferry access to Isla Mujeres without a premium price tag. November through April brings the most settled weather.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-costa-mujeres': {
    activities: `Riu Palace Costa Mujeres sits on the calmer Costa Mujeres coast north of Cancun, with a genuinely good beach, a kids' club, a waterpark-style pool area for both little and big kids, and the Riu chain's standard swim-up bar and nightly entertainment. Its newer, less crowded setting compared to the Hotel Zone is a real draw, and the Isla Mujeres ferry from nearby Punta Sam is an easy day trip. Reef snorkeling just offshore rounds out the water-based activities.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly 40–45 minutes north, Riu Palace Costa Mujeres benefits from Costa Mujeres's calmer, less developed coastline. Rooms and cleanliness both score exceptionally, and the beach holds up well too, at 7.5. It's a family-oriented resort with a genuine waterpark draw for kids of varying ages, positioned a notch above the standard Riu tier in service and finish. Its distance from downtown Cancun means fewer walkable off-site options, so plan on excursions, a rental car, or the resort's own shuttle for trips into town. November through April is the most reliable season for beach weather.`,
  },
  'hard-rock-hotel-cancun': {
    activities: `Hard Rock Hotel Cancun sits beachfront in the Hotel Zone with the brand's signature music-themed decor, a kids' club, tennis, a spa, and swim-up bars, plus live entertainment that leans into the Hard Rock identity more than a typical resort. The beach here rates well among Hotel Zone properties, supporting genuine swimming rather than just lounging. Coco Bongo, the Forum shopping mall, and MUSA snorkel and dive excursions are all a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Hard Rock Hotel Cancun occupies a solid Hotel Zone beach position, reflected in its 8 beach score. Service and room quality both rate well, consistent with the Hard Rock brand's polish. It's a family-friendly resort (pets are welcome too, a less common perk in the zone) built around music theming and entertainment rather than quiet relaxation. Book November through April for the calmest seas and lowest storm risk; the brand's live entertainment runs year-round regardless of season.`,
  },
  'paradisus-cancun': {
    activities: `Paradisus Cancun, part of Meliá's upscale all-inclusive brand, sits in the Hotel Zone with a strong beach, a golf course nearby, a kids' club, tennis, and a dive shop for reef excursions. Evenings bring a nightclub and organized entertainment, while the resort's overall polish sits a notch above the area's mid-tier chains. Isla Mujeres's ferry and the MUSA underwater museum's snorkel trips are both within easy reach for day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Paradisus Cancun benefits from a genuinely strong Hotel Zone beach (8.3) and consistently high cleanliness and location scores. It's a family resort with upscale positioning within the Meliá portfolio, offering more polish than many nearby mid-tier chains at a similar price bracket. Food and service both score solidly without being outright standouts. It suits families wanting a step up in design and service level while staying centrally located. Late fall through spring remains the most settled season for beach-focused travel.`,
  },
  'hilton-cancun': {
    activities: `Hilton Cancun runs a full family program — kids' and teens' clubs, a heated pool, yoga classes, and a spa — with pets welcome, a less common feature among Hotel Zone resorts. The beach out front is narrow and affected by erosion, so most guests treat the resort's pools as the primary swimming option rather than the ocean. Coco Bongo, the Forum shopping center, and Isla Mujeres's ferry terminal are all a short drive from the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Hilton Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone with rooms, cleanliness, and service all rating strongly. Its clear weak point is the beach, at 3.5 — one of the lower marks in our database, reflecting significant erosion along this particular stretch of the zone that has left little usable sand. Book it for the room quality, service, and Hilton reliability rather than for beachfront lounging, and lean on the resort's pools instead. It's a solid family pick, pet-friendly too. November through April is the calmest season for what beach access there is.`,
  },
  'dreams-playa-mujeres-golf-and-spa-resort': {
    activities: `Dreams Playa Mujeres pairs a genuine golf course with a strong family program — kids' and teens' clubs (including one for under-4s), a lazy river, mini golf, and a waterpark-style pool for both younger and older kids. Its Costa Mujeres setting gives it a good beach relative to the Hotel Zone, and the resort's dining and pool scores both land solidly above average. Isla Mujeres's ferry from nearby Punta Sam and the area's golf courses round out the excursion options.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly 40–45 minutes north, Dreams Playa Mujeres benefits from Costa Mujeres's calmer coastline and a genuine golf draw uncommon among family resorts in this region. Food, pool, and room quality all score well, making it one of the more consistently strong performers in the Playa Mujeres area, and service holds up alongside them. It suits families wanting golf access alongside a full kids' program spanning toddlers through teens. November through April brings the most comfortable weather for both the beach and the course, with summer bringing higher humidity and a greater chance of rain.`,
  },
  'oleo-cancun-playa': {
    activities: `Óleo Cancún Playa sits in a quieter southern stretch of the Hotel Zone, about 20 minutes from the main nightlife strip, with a kids' club, tennis, snorkeling gear, and a swim-up bar. Its more tranquil positioning within the zone is a deliberate contrast to the busier northern hotels, making it a good fit for guests wanting beach access without constant foot traffic. Coco Bongo and the Forum shopping center remain a short drive away when guests want livelier evenings.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Óleo Cancún Playa sits roughly 20 minutes from the Hotel Zone's main nightlife hub, in a calmer pocket of the strip. Service and cleanliness both score exceptionally, and the beach holds up well too. Some guests flag unexpected charges and maintenance issues in older rooms, worth budgeting and expectation-setting for. It's a solid family option for travelers who want a relatively tranquil Hotel Zone stay rather than a central, high-energy one. November through April remains the calmest, driest window.`,
  },
  'ava-resort-cancun': {
    activities: `AVA Resort Cancun (which replaced the former Grand Oasis) is a large, high-energy property with dozens of restaurants and bars, a saltwater lagoon for kayaking and paddleboarding, a bowling alley, an arcade, and both kids' and teens' clubs. It leans into entertainment and nightlife more than most family resorts on this list, with a buzzy, high-volume atmosphere reviewers compare to a Las Vegas resort rather than a quiet beach escape. It's about ten minutes from Cancun's airport, making arrival unusually convenient.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport in about ten minutes — one of the shortest transfers in the Hotel Zone — AVA Resort Cancun opened in 2024 as a large-scale reimagining of the former Grand Oasis. Food, pool, atmosphere, and cleanliness all score strongly, reflecting genuinely upscale finishes and an oceanfront design with private balcony tubs in every room. The beach itself is a more modest strength, affected by sargassum at times, and the resort's scale and energy suit travelers looking for buzz over tranquility. Value draws some criticism for upselling. November through April is the calmer season.`,
  },
  'catalonia-playa-maroma': {
    activities: `Catalonia Playa Maroma sits on Playa Maroma, widely regarded as one of the better beaches on this coast, with calm, clear water backed by a kids' club, tennis, a dive shop, and snorkeling gear. The resort's beach is the clear headline feature, drawing repeat visitors specifically for it. Evening entertainment and a nightclub cover the resort side, while Xcaret and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue are both a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Catalonia Playa Maroma sits on the Riviera Maya's Playa Maroma stretch, prized locally for its unusually calm, clear water and soft sand. The beach score of 8.8 reflects that reputation and is genuinely the property's strongest mark. Food and atmosphere are more modest by comparison, at a lower price point than many nearby competitors. It suits families and couples specifically chasing beach quality over dining sophistication. November through April brings the calmest seas and clearest water for snorkeling.`,
  },
  'dreams-vista-cancun-golf-and-spa-resort': {
    activities: `Dreams Vista Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone with an extensive amenity list — a FlowRider, an arcade, a golf course nearby, windsurfing, and both kids' and teens' clubs — built for families wanting variety beyond the beach. Watersports rentals and a dive shop cover reef trips, while the pool and spa handle most of the daily recreation. Coco Bongo and the MUSA underwater museum's excursions are both a short drive from the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Dreams Vista Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone with rooms and sleep quality both scoring well. The beach is its clear weak point at 4 — among the lower marks in our database — reflecting a stretch of coastline that has lost significant sand to erosion over the years. The resort compensates with an unusually broad activity list (FlowRider, golf, watersports) that keeps families occupied on-site. Pets are welcome, a less common perk in the zone. November through April remains the most settled season, though the beach caveat holds regardless.`,
  },
  'moon-palace-nizuc': {
    activities: `Moon Palace Nizuc is one section of the large Moon Palace Cancun complex, with a 27-hole golf course, a FlowRider, an arcade, a waterpark-style pool area, and both kids' and teens' clubs. Its scale means restaurants, pools, and entertainment options across the wider complex are all accessible to guests staying in Nizuc. The beach is a secondary feature here; golf and the pool complex are the real draws.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, Moon Palace Nizuc sits south of the Hotel Zone near the airport, part of the large Palace Resorts golf and spa complex. Room quality and cleanliness both score well, and the golf course is a genuine differentiator among Cancun-area family resorts. The beach is the clear weak point at 3.8 — one of the lower marks in our database — so guests should plan on the pool complex and golf rather than oceanfront time. It suits families wanting resort scale and golf access. November through April is the most reliable season for both golf and pool weather.`,
  },
  'dreams-jade-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Dreams Jade sits on the Puerto Morelos coast with a lazy river, heated pool, archery, a dive shop, fishing charters, and both kids' and teens' clubs (plus one for under-4s). The reef-protected marine park just offshore limits open beach but supports snorkeling on calm days. Puerto Morelos's low-key town center, with its market and seafood restaurants, is a short drive for guests wanting to leave the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 20–25 minutes, Dreams Jade benefits from being closer to the airport than most Playa del Carmen or Tulum-area resorts. Value and room quality both score well. The beach rates a more modest 4.8, consistent with Puerto Morelos's reef-protected coastline generally offering less open sand than resorts further south. It's a family-friendly resort with a strong kids' program across age groups, well suited to travelers prioritizing convenience and pool/lazy-river time over a wide beach. November through April remains the calmest season.`,
  },
  'grand-sirenis-riviera-maya-resort': {
    activities: `Grand Sirenis Riviera Maya Resort sits on a roughly two-mile stretch of the Akumal coastline, with a genuine coral reef close enough to shore for daily snorkeling — sea turtles, rays, and reef fish are common sightings right off the beach. A kids' club, lazy river, dive shop, and tennis round out the on-site program. Tulum's ruins and cenotes are within a short drive, making this a convenient base for exploring both the reef and the archaeological sites further south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This resort is reached via Tulum International Airport rather than Cancun, reflecting its position further down the coast near Akumal. Sleep quality and value both score reasonably well, and the snorkeling reputation here is genuinely strong despite a middling 4.3 beach score — guest reviews describe patches of the shoreline as rocky even as they praise the marine life just offshore. Food is a more modest mark. It suits families wanting reef access and Tulum proximity over a classic soft-sand beach. November through April brings the calmest, clearest water for snorkeling.`,
  },
  'iberostar-selection-riviera-cancun': {
    activities: `Iberostar Selection Riviera Cancun sits on the Puerto Morelos coast within Iberostar's upscale "Selection" tier, with a kids' club, archery, tennis, yoga classes, and a dive shop for reef trips into the protected marine park offshore. Fishing charters and a spa round out the activity list. Puerto Morelos's fishing-village center, quieter and smaller than Cancun or Playa del Carmen, is a short drive for a lower-key alternative to resort dining.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 20–25 minutes, this Iberostar Selection property benefits from proximity to the airport, though its location score is a touch lower than sister properties, reflecting the relative remove from Playa del Carmen's town center. Cleanliness and service both score well, positioning it as a step up from Iberostar's standard tier. The beach is a moderate 5.5, typical for this reef-protected stretch of coast. It suits families wanting resort polish with an easy airport transfer. November through April remains the most settled season.`,
  },
  'wyndham-alltra-playa-del-carmen': {
    activities: `Wyndham Alltra Playa del Carmen is an adults-only resort centrally located near Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, with beach cabanas, several restaurants, hot stone massages, and lively entertainment that leans into the town's energetic character. Its central position makes walking to Fifth Avenue's shops, bars, and the Cozumel ferry terminal genuinely practical rather than requiring a taxi.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 45 minutes, Wyndham Alltra Playa del Carmen sits centrally enough to walk to Fifth Avenue, a genuine advantage over resorts further from town. Location and service both score well. The beach is the honest caveat — erosion has left parts of the shoreline with little sand, compounded by seasonal sargassum roughly May through October — so guests should treat the beach as a bonus rather than the main draw. It's an adults-only, energetic property suited to couples wanting nightlife and town access over a classic Riviera Maya beach. November through April is the calmer season.`,
  },
  'hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya sits near Puerto Aventuras with the brand's music theming, a lazy river, an arcade, a kids' club, tennis, fishing, and a waterpark-style pool area for both younger and older kids. The marina town of Puerto Aventuras, with its dolphin encounter facility and golf course, is close by, and Xpu-Ha beach offers an alternative stretch of sand for guests wanting to supplement the resort's own shoreline.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, about 50 minutes south, Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya sits near the Puerto Aventuras marina, further from the airport than Cancun's Hotel Zone properties. Room quality and cleanliness both score well, consistent with the brand's polish. The beach is more modest at 4.5, so guests focused on beach time might supplement with a trip to nearby Xpu-Ha. It's a family resort built around music theming and an extensive activity list rather than a top-tier beach. November through April remains the most settled season.`,
  },
  'grand-palladium-select-costa-mujeres': {
    activities: `Grand Palladium Select Costa Mujeres sits on the calmer Costa Mujeres coast north of Cancun, sharing grounds with its Family Selection wing, with a genuinely good beach, kids' and teens' clubs, a waterpark-style pool for younger kids, tennis, and a spa. The Isla Mujeres ferry from nearby Punta Sam and the area's newer golf courses are both within reach for excursions beyond the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly 40–45 minutes north, Grand Palladium Select Costa Mujeres benefits from Costa Mujeres's calmer, less crowded coastline compared to the Hotel Zone. Beach and sleep quality both score well, and room quality holds up solidly too. Value is a slightly softer mark relative to its sister Palladium properties. It's a family resort well suited to guests wanting a good beach outside Cancun's busiest strip. November through April is the most reliable season for beach weather.`,
  },
};
